'''Shinto Five Texts''' (shinto gobusho) are the fundamental scriptures of {{ill|ill|Ise Shinto|ja|伊勢神道}} (Watarai Shinto), comprising the following five texts:
* ''{{ill|ill|Tenshoza Ise Nisho Kotai Jingu Go Chinza Shidai Ki|ja|天照坐伊勢二所皇太神宮御鎮座次第記}}'' ("Account of the Enshrinement of the Two Ise Grand Shrines")
* ''{{ill|ill|Ise Nisho Kotai Jingu Go Chinza Denki|ja|伊勢二所皇太神御鎮座伝記}}'' ("Records of the Enshrinement of the Two Ise Grand Shrines")
* ''{{ill|ill|Toyouke Kotai Jingu Go Chinza Honki|ja|豊受皇太神御鎮座本紀}}'' ("The Fundamental Record of the Enshrinement of Toyouke Grand Shrine")
* ''{{ill|ill|Zo Ise Nisho Daijingu Hoki Honki|ja|造伊勢二所太神宮宝基本記}}'' ("The Fundamental Record of the Treasures of the Two Ise Grand Shrines")
* ''{{ill|ill|Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|ja|倭姫命世記}}'' ("The Chronicle of Yamatohime no Mikoto")

Although these texts claim to have been compiled before the {{ill|ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代}}, it is widely believed that they were actually written during the {{ill|ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代}} by {{ill|ill|Watarai Yukitada|ja|度会行忠}} and other priests of the {{ill|ill|Outer Shrine|ja|豊受大神宮}} of {{ill|ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮}}.

== Overview ==
Research from the fields of {{ill|ill|History|ja|歴史学}} and {{ill|ill|Japanese literature|ja|日本文学}} suggests that the {{ill|ill|Watarai clan|ja|度会氏}}, who served as priests at the Outer Shrine, compiled these texts to elevate the status of the Outer Shrine to be equal or even superior to the {{ill|ill|Inner Shrine|ja|皇大神宮}}, which enshrines {{ill|ill|Amaterasu Omikami|ja|天照大神}}. To achieve this, they identified {{ill|ill|Toyouke Omikami|ja|豊受大神}}—the deity enshrined at the Outer Shrine—with {{ill|ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi-no-Kami|ja|天之御中主神}} and {{ill|ill|Kuni-no-Tokotachi-no-Kami|ja|国之常立神}}, arguing that Toyouke possessed a higher, more universal divine status than Amaterasu.<ref>{{Cite book|title=偽書が揺るがせた日本史 |date=2020年3月25日 |publisher=（株）山川出版社 |pages=82-84 |author=原田実}}</ref>

Ise Shinto itself was formulated as a critique of the {{ill|ill|Honji Suijaku|ja|本地垂迹}} theory through its doctrine of {{ill|ill|Shinpon Butsuseki|ja|神本仏迹説}}, which asserted the primacy of Shinto over Buddhism. However, it has been suggested that the logic underlying these foundational texts of Ise Shinto was influenced by Buddhist thought, particularly the interpretations found in works such as ''{{ill|ill|Yamato Katsuragi Hozan Ki|ja|大和葛城宝山記}}'', a Shinto theory developed from the perspective of {{ill|ill|Shugendo|ja|修験道}}.

During the {{ill|ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}}, {{ill|ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和}}, a priest of the {{ill|ill|Tōshōgū Shrine|ja|東照宮}} in {{ill|ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国}}, vehemently criticized the Shinto Five Texts as {{ill|ill|forgeries|ja|偽書}}.{{Sfn|必携日本史用語}}

