== Description == According to studies in {{ill|history|ja|歴史学}} and {{ill|Japanese literature|ja|日本文学}}, these texts were likely authored by members of the {{ill|Watarai clan|ja|度会氏}}, who served as priests at the {{ill|Outer Shrine of Ise|ja|豊受大神宮}}. Their objective was to elevate the status of the Outer Shrine to equal or even surpass that of the {{ill|Inner Shrine|ja|皇大神宮}}, which enshrines {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神}}. To achieve this, they identified {{ill|Toyouke Omikami|ja|豊受大神}} (the deity of the Outer Shrine) with both {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天之御中主神}} and {{ill|Kuni-no-Tokotachi|ja|国之常立神}}, thereby asserting Toyouke's universal divine supremacy over Amaterasu.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|title=偽書が揺るがせた日本史|date=2020-03-25|publisher=山川出版社|pages=82-84|author=原田 実}}</ref>
Although Ise Shinto was fundamentally based on the *{{ill|Shinpon Butsujaku Setsu|ja|神本仏迹説}}* ("Shinto as the Source, Buddhism as the Trace") as a critique of the {{ill|honji suijaku|ja|本地垂迹説}} theory, the logical framework of these texts shows clear influences from Buddhist thought, especially from the {{ill|Shugendo|ja|修験道}} tradition, as seen in works like *{{ill|The Treasures of Mount Katsuragi in Yamato|ja|大和葛城宝山記}}*.
During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}}, the *Five Texts of Shinto* faced harsh criticism from scholars such as {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和}}, a Shinto priest of the {{ill|Toshogu Shrine|ja|東照宮}} in Owari Province, who denounced them as forgeries.{{Sfn|必携日本史用語}}
