[[Category:Unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:deprecated qq start]][[Category:deprecated qq end]] [[Category:deprecated qq start]]<!--Five Books of Shinto-->[[Category:deprecated qq end]] [[Category:Five Books of Shinto]] [[ja:%E7%A5%9E%E9%81%93%E4%BA%94%E9%83%A8%E6%9B%B8]] [[Category:Unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:deprecated qq start]][[Category:deprecated qq end]] [[Category:deprecated qq start]]<!--Five Books of Shinto-->[[Category:deprecated qq end]] [[en:Five Books of Shinto]] [[Category:Unsorted completion categories]] [[Category:deprecated qq start]][[Category:deprecated qq end]] [[Category:deprecated qq start]]<!--Five Books of Shinto-->[[Category:deprecated qq end]] [[Category:refreshing imports]] [[Category:pgoodbye $1]] [[Category:Five Books of Shinto]] [[Category:pgoodbye $1]] [[Category:nnn]] [[Category:kk]] [[Category:Five Books of Shinto]] [[en:Five Books of Shinto]] [[en:Five Books of Shinto]] '''The Five Texts of Shinto''' (神道五部書, *Shintō Gobusho*)
== Overview == The *Five Texts of Shinto* are the foundational scriptures of {{ill|Ise Shinto|ja|伊勢神道}} (also known as Watarai Shinto). These texts include the following five scriptures:
* *The Record of the Enshrinement of the Two Imperial Grand Shrines of Amaterasu in Ise* (天照坐伊勢二所皇太神宮御鎮座次第記) * *The Biography of the Enshrinement of the Two Imperial Grand Shrines of Ise* (伊勢二所皇太神御鎮座伝記) * *The Original Chronicle of the Enshrinement of the Imperial Grand Deity Toyouke* (豊受皇太神御鎮座本紀) * *The Original Record of Treasures and Foundations of the Two Great Shrines of Ise* (造伊勢二所太神宮宝基本記) * {{ill|The Chronicle of Princess Yamato-hime|ja|倭姫命世記|1=Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki}}
While the colophons of these texts claim origins dating back to before the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代}}, it is widely believed that they were actually composed during the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代}} by Watarai Yukitada and other priests of the Outer Shrine of Ise.
== Description == According to studies in {{ill|history|ja|歴史学}} and {{ill|Japanese literature|ja|日本文学}}, these texts were likely authored by members of the {{ill|Watarai clan|ja|度会氏}}, who served as priests at the {{ill|Outer Shrine of Ise|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮}}. Their objective was to elevate the status of the Outer Shrine to equal or even surpass that of the {{ill|Inner Shrine|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮}}, which enshrines {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神}}. To achieve this, they identified {{ill|Toyouke Omikami|ja|豊受大神}} (the deity of the Outer Shrine) with both {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天之御中主神}} and {{ill|Kuni-no-Tokotachi|ja|国之常立神}}, thereby asserting Toyouke's universal divine supremacy over Amaterasu.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|title=偽書が揺るがせた日本史|date=2020-03-25|publisher=山川出版社|pages=82-84|author=原田 実}}</ref>
Although Ise Shinto was fundamentally based on the *{{ill|Shinpon Butsujaku Setsu|ja|神本仏迹説}}* ("Shinto as the Source, Buddhism as the Trace") as a critique of the {{ill|honji suijaku|ja|本地垂迹説}} theory, the logical framework of these texts shows clear influences from Buddhist thought, especially from the {{ill|Shugendo|ja|修験道}} tradition, as seen in works like *{{ill|The Treasures of Mount Katsuragi in Yamato|ja|大和葛城宝山記}}*.
During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代}}, the *Five Texts of Shinto* faced harsh criticism from scholars such as {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和}}, a Shinto priest of the {{ill|Toshogu Shrine|ja|東照宮}} in Owari Province, who denounced them as forgeries.{{Sfn|必携日本史用語}}
