'''The Five Texts of Shinto''' (神道五部書, *Shintō Gobusho*)

== Overview ==
The *Five Texts of Shinto* are the foundational scriptures of {{ill|Ise Shinto|ja|伊勢神道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (also known as Watarai Shinto). These texts include the following five scriptures:

* *The Record of the Enshrinement of the Two Imperial Grand Shrines of Amaterasu in Ise* (天照坐伊勢二所皇太神宮御鎮座次第記)
* *The Biography of the Enshrinement of the Two Imperial Grand Shrines of Ise* (伊勢二所皇太神御鎮座伝記)
* *The Original Chronicle of the Enshrinement of the Imperial Grand Deity Toyouke* (豊受皇太神御鎮座本紀)
* *The Original Record of Treasures and Foundations of the Two Great Shrines of Ise* (造伊勢二所太神宮宝基本記)
* {{ill|The Chronicle of Princess Yamato-hime|ja|倭姫命世記|1=Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|qq=draft|qq=draft}}

While the colophons of these texts claim origins dating back to before the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, it is widely believed that they were actually composed during the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}} by Watarai Yukitada and other priests of the Outer Shrine of Ise.

== Description ==
According to studies in {{ill|history|ja|歴史学|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Japanese literature|ja|日本文学|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, these texts were likely authored by members of the {{ill|Watarai clan|ja|度会氏|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, who served as priests at the {{ill|Outer Shrine of Ise|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. Their objective was to elevate the status of the Outer Shrine to equal or even surpass that of the {{ill|Inner Shrine|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, which enshrines {{ill|Amaterasu|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft}}. To achieve this, they identified {{ill|Toyouke Omikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft}} (the deity of the Outer Shrine) with both {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天之御中主神|qq=draft|qq=draft}} and {{ill|Kuni-no-Tokotachi|ja|国之常立神|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, thereby asserting Toyouke's universal divine supremacy over Amaterasu.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|title=偽書が揺るがせた日本史|date=2020-03-25|publisher=山川出版社|pages=82-84|author=原田 実}}</ref>

Although Ise Shinto was fundamentally based on the *{{ill|Shinpon Butsujaku Setsu|ja|神本仏迹説|qq=draft|qq=draft}}* ("Shinto as the Source, Buddhism as the Trace") as a critique of the {{ill|honji suijaku|ja|本地垂迹説|qq=draft|qq=draft}} theory, the logical framework of these texts shows clear influences from Buddhist thought, especially from the {{ill|Shugendo|ja|修験道|qq=draft|qq=draft}} tradition, as seen in works like *{{ill|The Treasures of Mount Katsuragi in Yamato|ja|大和葛城宝山記|qq=draft|qq=draft}}*.

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, the *Five Texts of Shinto* faced harsh criticism from scholars such as {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和|qq=draft|qq=draft}}, a Shinto priest of the {{ill|Toshogu Shrine|ja|東照宮|qq=draft|qq=draft}} in Owari Province, who denounced them as forgeries.{{Sfn|必携日本史用語}}

