]]
'''Shinto Five Texts''' (shinto gobusho) are the fundamental scriptures of {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|lt=Ise Grand Shrine|lt=Ise Shinto|ja|伊勢神道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Shinto|qq=}} (Watarai Shinto), comprising the following five texts:
* ''{{ill|Tenshoza Ise Nisho Kotai Jingu Go Chinza Shidai Ki|ja|天照坐伊勢二所皇太神宮御鎮座次第記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tenshoza Ise Nisho Kotai Jingu Go Chinza Shidai Ki|qq=}}'' ("Account of the Enshrinement of the Two Ise Grand Shrines")
* ''{{ill|Ise Nisho Kotai Jingu Go Chinza Denki|ja|伊勢二所皇太神御鎮座伝記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Nisho Kotai Jingu Go Chinza Denki|qq=}}'' ("Records of the Enshrinement of the Two Ise Grand Shrines")
* ''{{ill|Toyouke Kotai Jingu Go Chinza Honki|ja|豊受皇太神御鎮座本紀|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Kotai Jingu Go Chinza Honki|qq=}}'' ("The Fundamental Record of the Enshrinement of Toyouke Grand Shrine")
* ''{{ill|Zo Ise Nisho Daijingu Hoki Honki|ja|造伊勢二所太神宮宝基本記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Zo Ise Nisho Daijingu Hoki Honki|qq=}}'' ("The Fundamental Record of the Treasures of the Two Ise Grand Shrines")
* ''{{ill|Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|ja|倭姫命世記|1=Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|qq=}}'' ("The Chronicle of Yamatohime no Mikoto")

Although these texts claim to have been compiled before the {{ill|Nara period|ja|奈良時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Nara period|qq=}}, it is widely believed that they were actually written during the {{ill|Kamakura period|ja|鎌倉時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kamakura period|qq=}} by {{ill|Watarai Yukitada|ja|度会行忠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watarai Yukitada|qq=}} and other priests of the {{ill|Outer Shrine|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Outer Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Daijingu|qq=}} of {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|ja|伊勢神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Grand Shrine|qq=}}.

== Overview ==
Research from the fields of {{ill|History|ja|歴史学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/History|qq=}} and {{ill|Japanese literature|ja|日本文学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Japanese literature|qq=}} suggests that the {{ill|Watarai clan|ja|度会氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watarai clan|qq=}}, who served as priests at the Outer Shrine, compiled these texts to elevate the status of the Outer Shrine to be equal or even superior to the {{ill|Inner Shrine|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inner Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōtai Jingū|qq=}}, which enshrines {{ill|Amaterasu Omikami|ja|天照大神|1=Amaterasu|lt=Amaterasu Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu Omikami|13=User:Immanuelle/Amaterasu|qq=}}. To achieve this, they identified {{ill|Toyouke Omikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Omikami|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke-hime|qq=}}—the deity enshrined at the Outer Shrine—with {{ill|Ame-no-Minakanushi|ja|天之御中主神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ame-no-Minakanushi|qq=}} and {{ill|Kuni-no-Tokotachi-no-Kami|ja|国之常立神|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Kuni-no-Tokotachi-no-Kami|qq=}}, arguing that Toyouke possessed a higher, more universal divine status than Amaterasu.<ref>{{Cite book|title=偽書が揺るがせた日本史 |date=2020th year 3月25日 |publisher=（株）山川出版社 |pages=82-84 |author=原田実}}</ref>

Ise Shinto itself was formulated as a critique of the {{ill|Honji Suijaku|ja|本地垂迹|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Honji Suijaku|qq=}} theory through its doctrine of {{ill|Shinpon Butsuseki|ja|神本仏迹説|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinpon Butsuseki|qq=}}, which asserted the primacy of Shinto over Buddhism. However, it has been suggested that the logic underlying these foundational texts of Ise Shinto was influenced by Buddhist thought, particularly the interpretations found in works such as ''{{ill|Yamato Katsuragi Hozan Ki|ja|大和葛城宝山記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Katsuragi Hozan Ki|qq=}}'', a Shinto theory developed from the perspective of {{ill|Shugendo|ja|修験道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shugendo|qq=}}.

During the {{ill|Edo period|ja|江戸時代|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Edo period|qq=}}, {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshimi Yukikazu|qq=}}, a priest of the {{ill|Tōshōgū Shrine|ja|東照宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Tōshōgū Shrine|qq=}} in {{ill|Owari Province|ja|尾張国|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Owari Province|qq=}}, vehemently criticized the Shinto Five Texts as {{ill|forgeries|ja|偽書|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/forgeries|qq=}}.{{Sfn|必携日本史用語}}

