Research from the fields of {{ill|History|ja|歴史学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/History|qq=}} and [[:en:Japanese literature|Japanese literature]] suggests that the {{ill|Watarai clan|ja|度会氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watarai clan|qq=}}, who served as priests at the Outer Shrine, compiled these texts to elevate the status of the Outer Shrine to be equal or even superior to the {{ill|Inner Shrine|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inner Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōtai Jingū|qq=}}, which enshrines [[:en:Amaterasu|Amaterasu Ōmikami]]. To achieve this, they identified {{ill|Toyouke Omikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Omikami|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke-hime|qq=}}—the deity enshrined at the Outer Shrine—with [[:en:Ame-no-Minakanushi|Ame-no-Minakanushi]] and [[:en:Kuni-no-Tokotachi|Kuni-no-Tokotachi-no-Kami]], arguing that Toyouke possessed a higher, more universal divine status than Amaterasu.<ref>{{Cite book|title=偽書が揺るがせた日本史 |date=2020th year 3月25日 |publisher=（株）山川出版社 |pages=82-84 |author=原田実}}</ref>

Ise Shinto itself was formulated as a critique of the [[:en:Honji suijaku|Honji Suijaku]] theory through its doctrine of {{ill|Shinpon Butsuseki|ja|神本仏迹説|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinpon Butsuseki|qq=}}, which asserted the primacy of Shinto over Buddhism. However, it has been suggested that the logic underlying these foundational texts of Ise Shinto was influenced by Buddhist thought, particularly the interpretations found in works such as ''{{ill|Yamato Katsuragi Hozan Ki|ja|大和葛城宝山記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Katsuragi Hozan Ki|qq=}}'', a Shinto theory developed from the perspective of [[:en:Shugendō|Shugendo]].

During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshimi Yukikazu|qq=}}, a priest of the [[:en:Tōshō-gū|Tōshōgū Shrine]] in [[:en:Owari Province|Owari Province]], vehemently criticized the Shinto Five Texts as {{ill|forgeries|ja|偽書|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/forgeries|qq=}}.{{Sfn|必携日本史用語}}

