'''The Five Texts of Shinto''' (神道五部書, *Shintō Gobusho*)

== Overview ==
The *Five Texts of Shinto* are the foundational scriptures of {{ill|Ise Grand Shrine|lt=Ise Grand Shrine|lt=Ise Shinto|ja|伊勢神道|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Ise Shinto|qq=}} (also known as Watarai Shinto). These texts include the following five scriptures:

* *The Record of the Enshrinement of the Two Imperial Grand Shrines of Amaterasu in Ise* (天照坐伊勢二所皇太神宮御鎮座次第記)
* *The Biography of the Enshrinement of the Two Imperial Grand Shrines of Ise* (伊勢二所皇太神御鎮座伝記)
* *The Original Chronicle of the Enshrinement of the Imperial Grand Deity Toyouke* (豊受皇太神御鎮座本紀)
* *The Original Record of Treasures and Foundations of the Two Great Shrines of Ise* (造伊勢二所太神宮宝基本記)
* {{ill|The Chronicle of Princess Yamato-hime|ja|倭姫命世記|1=Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/The Chronicle of Princess Yamato-hime|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamatohime no Mikoto Seiki|qq=}}

While the colophons of these texts claim origins dating back to before the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]], it is widely believed that they were actually composed during the [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]] by Watarai Yukitada and other priests of the Outer Shrine of Ise.

== Description ==
According to studies in {{ill|history|ja|歴史学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/history|qq=}} and [[:en:Japanese literature|Japanese literature]], these texts were likely authored by members of the {{ill|Watarai clan|ja|度会氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watarai clan|qq=}}, who served as priests at the {{ill|Outer Shrine of Ise|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Outer Shrine of Ise|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Daijingu|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}. Their objective was to elevate the status of the Outer Shrine to equal or even surpass that of the {{ill|Inner Shrine|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inner Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōtai Jingū|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, which enshrines [[:en:Amaterasu|Amaterasu Ōmikami]]. To achieve this, they identified {{ill|Toyouke Omikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-hime|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Omikami|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke-hime|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to トヨウケビメ}} (the deity of the Outer Shrine) with both [[:en:Ame-no-Minakanushi|Ame-no-Minakanushi]] and [[:en:Kuni-no-Tokotachi|Kuni-no-Tokotachi]], thereby asserting Toyouke's universal divine supremacy over Amaterasu.<ref>{{Cite book|ja|title=偽書が揺るがせた日本史|date=2020-03-25|publisher=山川出版社|pages=82-84|author=原田 実}}</ref>

Although Ise Shinto was fundamentally based on the *{{ill|Shinpon Butsujaku Setsu|ja|神本仏迹説|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinpon Butsujaku Setsu|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 本地垂迹}}* ("Shinto as the Source, Buddhism as the Trace") as a critique of the {{ill|honji suijaku|ja|本地垂迹説|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/honji suijaku|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 本地垂迹}} theory, the logical framework of these texts shows clear influences from Buddhist thought, especially from the [[:en:Shugendō|Shugendo]] tradition, as seen in works like *{{ill|The Treasures of Mount Katsuragi in Yamato|ja|大和葛城宝山記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/The Treasures of Mount Katsuragi in Yamato|qq=}}*.

During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], the *Five Texts of Shinto* faced harsh criticism from scholars such as {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshimi Yukikazu|qq=}}, a Shinto priest of the [[:en:Tōshō-gū|Toshogu Shrine]] in Owari Province, who denounced them as forgeries.{{Sfn|必携日本史用語}}

