Although these texts claim to have been compiled before the [[:en:Nara period|Nara period]], it is widely believed that they were actually written during the [[:en:Kamakura period|Kamakura period]] by {{ill|Watarai Yukitada|ja|度会行忠|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watarai Yukitada|qq=|1=Watarai Yukitada|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q17217919}} and other priests of the {{ill|Outer Shrine|ja|豊受大神宮|1=Toyouke Daijingu|2=ja|3=豊受大神宮|4=zh|5=豐受大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Outer Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Daijingu|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}} of [[:en:Ise Shrine|Ise Grand Shrine]].

== Overview ==
Research from the fields of {{ill|History|ja|歴史学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/History|qq=|1=study of history|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q1066186}} and [[:en:Japanese literature|Japanese literature]] suggests that the {{ill|Watarai clan|ja|度会氏|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Watarai clan|qq=}}, who served as priests at the Outer Shrine, compiled these texts to elevate the status of the Outer Shrine to be equal or even superior to the {{ill|Inner Shrine|ja|皇大神宮|1=Kōtai Jingū|2=ja|3=皇大神宮|4=zh|5=皇大神宮|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Inner Shrine|13=User:Immanuelle/Kōtai Jingū|qq=|comment=enwiki is a redirect}}, which enshrines [[:en:Amaterasu|Amaterasu Ōmikami]]. To achieve this, they identified {{ill|Toyouke Omikami|ja|豊受大神|lt=Toyouke Ōmikami|1=Toyouke-Ōmikami|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke Omikami|13=User:Immanuelle/Toyouke-hime|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to トヨウケビメ|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q2983724}}—the deity enshrined at the Outer Shrine—with [[:en:Ame-no-Minakanushi|Ame-no-Minakanushi]] and [[:en:Kuni-no-Tokotachi|Kuni-no-Tokotachi-no-Kami]], arguing that Toyouke possessed a higher, more universal divine status than Amaterasu.<ref>{{Cite book|title=偽書が揺るがせた日本史 |date=2020th year 3月25日 |publisher=（株）山川出版社 |pages=82-84 |author=原田実}}</ref>

Ise Shinto itself was formulated as a critique of the [[:en:Honji suijaku|Honji Suijaku]] theory through its doctrine of {{ill|Shinpon Butsuseki|ja|神本仏迹説|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Shinpon Butsuseki|qq=|ja_comment=jawiki redirects to 本地垂迹|1=honji suijaku|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q3080781}}, which asserted the primacy of Shinto over Buddhism. However, it has been suggested that the logic underlying these foundational texts of Ise Shinto was influenced by Buddhist thought, particularly the interpretations found in works such as ''{{ill|Yamato Katsuragi Hozan Ki|ja|大和葛城宝山記|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yamato Katsuragi Hozan Ki|qq=|1=Yamato Katsuragi Hozan Ki|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q11433558}}'', a Shinto theory developed from the perspective of [[:en:Shugendō|Shugendo]].

During the [[:en:Edo period|Edo period]], {{ill|Yoshimi Yukikazu|ja|吉見幸和|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Yoshimi Yukikazu|qq=|1=Yoshimi Yoshikazu|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q63131320}}, a priest of the [[:en:Tōshō-gū|Tōshōgū Shrine]] in [[:en:Owari Province|Owari Province]], vehemently criticized the Shinto Five Texts as {{ill|forgeries|ja|偽書|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/forgeries|qq=|1=forged document|comment=changed title based on wikidata|WD=Q42757690}}.{{Sfn|必携日本史用語}}

